Cable management proving to be hell :ptv-unimpressed:
Ahh yes, that's always hours of enjoyment.
What's really holding me up is the suplemental 4+4 pin power for the cpu
I have 2 of them, this case is really long, and the cables just barely reach up there
Oh I hated that back in the day I had the same issue in my P180 and I think a ABIT AW8 motherboard.
Also, Cooler Master's design is a bit eh
The PSU was bottom mounted so that was a bit of a stretch.
It's just like I though, most of the storage spaces require access to the backside in order to mount the drives :/
2 of them I was right about, need access to underneath the mobo to add them
So you have to take out the mobo if you want to add some or remove some later
The other side panel doesn't just remove? Maybe not designed like that.
So forget what I said earlier about the ssd mounting
There are these little screws for SSDs and all 2.5" drives mount on these rubber pads
Apparently you screw in the screws, and then plug in the holes on the rubber pads, lol
Not exactly the most secure method, but super easy to work with
I'm trying to figure out what to do with my AIO now
The whole thing can't fit inside the case
So either I mount the radiator in the front, or put the fans for it in the top section on the other side
But idk if their cables will be long enough to reach the stuff from the pump?
I think in the future, I'll just buy a prebuilt :ptv-pouty:
That's what I always worried about, cases get cramped fast adding waterblocks and radiators.
I had a "Coolit" Peltier cooler at one point, I missed just having space in the case to tinker. lol
Well at least it's nice to look at now
We'll see in 2 - 3 years if I did too much thermal paste xD
It seems like too much, then I used a paper towel to sorta pre-spread and remove some
If it drops out like melty ice cream... It's too much. xD
One little metal bb sized dab is supposed to be good.
Yeah the prespreading helps even it out, makes sense bcuz if you look at how Intel preapplies the thermal paste to its OEM coolers it's distributed in 3 flat segments.
So coverage does matter to a degree.
